{
  "The largest internal organ in the body is the:": "",
  "Heart": "",
  "Stomach": "",
  "Liver": "",
  "Kidney": "",
  "The liver is the largest internal organ, weighing approximately 1.5 kilograms in adults. It is located in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen and performs over 500 metabolic functions essential for life.": "",
  "The liver produces which substance that aids in fat digestion?": "",
  "Insulin": "",
  "Amylase": "",
  "Pepsin": "",
  "Bile": "",
  "The liver continuously produces bile, a yellow-green fluid containing bile salts, cholesterol, bilirubin, and phospholipids. Bile salts act as emulsifiers that break large fat globules into smaller droplets, increasing the surface area available for pancreatic lipase.": "",
  "The gallbladder stores and concentrates which substance?": "",
  "Pancreatic juice": "",
  "Gastric acid": "",
  "The gallbladder is a small pear-shaped sac on the inferior surface of the liver that stores and concentrates bile by absorbing water and ions. When fat enters the duodenum, CCK triggers gallbladder contraction, releasing concentrated bile into the duodenum.": "",
  "The liver synthesizes which important plasma proteins?": "",
  "Only digestive enzymes": "",
  "Only antibodies (immunoglobulins)": "",
  "Hemoglobin and myoglobin": "",
  "Albumin, clotting factors (fibrinogen, prothrombin), and complement proteins": "",
  "The liver is the body's primary protein factory, producing albumin (which maintains plasma oncotic pressure), most clotting factors (including fibrinogen and prothrombin), and many other plasma proteins. Liver failure leads to hypoalbuminemia and coagulopathy.": "",
  "Bilirubin is a breakdown product of:": "",
  "Glucose metabolism": "",
  "Dietary fat": "",
  "Hemoglobin from old red blood cells": "",
  "Dietary protein": "",
  "When old red blood cells are destroyed by macrophages in the spleen and liver, the heme portion of hemoglobin is converted to biliverdin and then to bilirubin. The liver conjugates bilirubin and excretes it in bile, giving feces their characteristic brown color.": "",
  "The pancreas produces bicarbonate to:": "",
  "Neutralize acidic chyme entering the duodenum, creating an optimal pH for intestinal enzymes": "",
  "Emulsify fats in the small intestine": "",
  "Increase the acidity of chyme entering the duodenum": "",
  "Digest proteins in the stomach": "",
  "Pancreatic duct cells secrete a bicarbonate-rich fluid in response to secretin. This bicarbonate neutralizes the acidic chyme (pH 2) entering the duodenum from the stomach, raising the pH to approximately 7-8, which is the optimal range for pancreatic enzymes to function.": "",
  "Trypsinogen is activated in the duodenum by which enzyme?": "",
  "Enterokinase (enteropeptidase)": "",
  "Hydrochloric acid": "",
  "Salivary amylase": "",
  "Enterokinase (also called enteropeptidase) is a brush border enzyme in the duodenum that cleaves trypsinogen to produce active trypsin. Trypsin then activates the other pancreatic zymogens (chymotrypsinogen, proelastase, procarboxypeptidase), initiating a proteolytic cascade.": "",
  "The largest salivary gland is the:": "",
  "Parotid gland": "",
  "Minor salivary glands": "",
  "Submandibular gland": "",
  "Sublingual gland": "",
  "The parotid gland is the largest of the three major salivary glands, located anterior to each ear. It produces primarily serous (watery, enzyme-rich) saliva containing salivary amylase and is the gland affected in mumps infection.": "",
  "The common bile duct delivers bile to the duodenum at the:": "",
  "Pyloric sphincter": "",
  "Ileocecal valve": "",
  "Hepatopancreatic ampulla (ampulla of Vater)": "",
  "Cardiac sphincter": "",
  "The common bile duct and the main pancreatic duct converge at the hepatopancreatic ampulla (ampulla of Vater) in the wall of the duodenum. The sphincter of Oddi controls the release of bile and pancreatic juice into the duodenal lumen.": "",
  "Gallstones (cholelithiasis) form when:": "",
  "The liver stops producing bile entirely": "",
  "The pancreas secretes enzymes into the gallbladder": "",
  "Cholesterol or bilirubin precipitates and crystallizes in the gallbladder": "",
  "Bile becomes too dilute in the gallbladder": "",
  "Gallstones form when the balance of bile components is disrupted, causing excess cholesterol or bilirubin to precipitate and crystallize. Risk factors include obesity, female sex, age over 40, and rapid weight loss (remembered by the mnemonic: Fat, Female, Fertile, Forty, Fair).": "",
  "What is bile?": "",
  "A mucous secretion from the stomach lining that protects against acid": "",
  "A yellow-green fluid produced by the liver containing bile salts, cholesterol, bilirubin, and phospholipids that emulsifies fats in the small intestine": "",
  "A hormone secreted by the gallbladder that stimulates fat absorption": "",
  "A digestive enzyme produced by the pancreas that chemically breaks down fats": "",
  "Bile is produced continuously by hepatocytes in the liver and is composed of bile salts (the active emulsifying agents), cholesterol, bilirubin (a waste pigment), phospholipids, and water. It does not contain digestive enzymes but plays a critical role in fat digestion by emulsifying large fat globules into tiny droplets.": "",
  "What is jaundice?": "",
  "A condition caused by excessive iron deposition in the skin": "",
  "A bacterial infection of the gallbladder that causes abdominal pain": "",
  "A yellow discoloration of the skin and sclera (whites of the eyes) caused by elevated bilirubin levels in the blood": "",
  "A deficiency of bile salts causing pale-colored stools": "",
  "Jaundice (icterus) occurs when bilirubin accumulates in the blood above 2-3 mg/dL, depositing in the skin and sclera and causing a characteristic yellow color. It can result from excessive red blood cell breakdown (hemolytic), liver disease (hepatocellular), or bile duct obstruction (obstructive/post-hepatic).": "",
  "What is cirrhosis?": "",
  "A benign fatty infiltration of the liver that has no clinical consequences": "",
  "An acute viral infection of the liver that resolves within weeks": "",
  "An autoimmune condition that only affects the gallbladder": "",
  "Chronic, irreversible scarring (fibrosis) of the liver in which functional hepatocytes are replaced by fibrous tissue, impairing liver function": "",
  "Cirrhosis represents the end stage of chronic liver disease in which repeated injury (from alcohol, hepatitis viruses, or other causes) triggers progressive fibrosis that replaces normal liver architecture with scar tissue. This distorts the hepatic vasculature, leading to portal hypertension, liver failure, and increased risk of hepatocellular carcinoma.": "",
  "What is hepatitis?": "",
  "Inflammation of the stomach lining from H. pylori infection": "",
  "A cancerous tumor of the pancreas": "",
  "Inflammation of the liver that can be caused by viruses (A, B, C), alcohol, drugs, or autoimmune conditions": "",
  "Inflammation of the gallbladder caused by gallstones": "",
  "Hepatitis literally means inflammation of the liver. The most common causes are hepatitis viruses (HAV transmitted fecal-oral, HBV and HCV transmitted through blood/body fluids), excessive alcohol consumption, certain medications, and autoimmune disorders. Chronic hepatitis B and C can progress to cirrhosis and liver cancer.": "",
  "What is pancreatitis?": "",
  "Inflammation of the pancreas, most commonly caused by gallstones or chronic alcohol use, in which digestive enzymes are prematurely activated and damage pancreatic tissue": "",
  "An infection of the pancreatic duct caused by bacteria that ascend from the duodenum, producing purulent inflammation and obstruction of exocrine secretions": "",
  "A hormonal disorder in which the pancreatic beta cells produce excessive insulin, causing chronic hypoglycemia, confusion, diaphoresis, and recurrent episodes of unconsciousness": "",
  "A congenital absence of the pancreas at birth, resulting in complete lack of digestive enzyme and insulin production requiring lifelong enzyme replacement and insulin therapy": "",
  "Pancreatitis occurs when pancreatic digestive enzymes (especially trypsin) are prematurely activated within the pancreas itself, causing autodigestion and severe inflammation. The two most common causes are gallstones (blocking the common bile/pancreatic duct) and alcohol abuse, and it presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back.": "",
  "What does the term 'cholelithiasis' mean?": "",
  "Surgical removal of the gallbladder": "",
  "Inflammation of the gallbladder": "",
  "The formation or presence of gallstones within the gallbladder": "",
  "Obstruction of the common bile duct by a tumor": "",
  "Cholelithiasis comes from the Greek roots 'chole' (bile), 'litho' (stone), and 'iasis' (condition), literally meaning the condition of having stones in the bile system. Most gallstones are cholesterol stones, though pigment stones (from bilirubin) also occur, particularly in patients with chronic hemolysis.": "",
  "What does the term 'hepatic biotransformation' mean?": "",
  "The liver's production of bile for fat digestion": "",
  "The liver's process of chemically modifying drugs, toxins, and metabolic waste products to make them less active and more water-soluble for excretion": "",
  "The regeneration of liver tissue after surgical resection": "",
  "The transformation of liver cells into cancer cells": "",
  "Hepatic biotransformation (also called drug metabolism or detoxification) involves Phase I reactions (oxidation, reduction, hydrolysis via cytochrome P450 enzymes) and Phase II reactions (conjugation with glucuronic acid, sulfate, or glutathione) that convert lipophilic substances into hydrophilic metabolites that can be excreted in bile or urine.": "",
  "What is lysozyme in the context of salivary function?": "",
  "A protein in saliva that binds to minerals and prevents tooth decay": "",
  "A digestive enzyme in saliva that breaks down starch into maltose": "",
  "A lipid-digesting enzyme secreted by the sublingual glands": "",
  "An antibacterial enzyme in saliva that destroys bacterial cell walls, serving as a first-line immune defense in the oral cavity": "",
  "Lysozyme is a natural antimicrobial enzyme found in saliva, tears, and nasal secretions. It cleaves the peptidoglycan bonds in bacterial cell walls, causing them to lyse. In saliva, lysozyme serves as a first-line defense against oral pathogens, helping to maintain oral health.": "",
  "What does the term 'enterohepatic circulation' mean?": "",
  "The movement of nutrients from enterocytes into hepatic sinusoids": "",
  "The recycling pathway in which bile salts are secreted by the liver into the intestine, reabsorbed in the terminal ileum, and returned to the liver via the portal vein for reuse": "",
  "The flow of blood from the heart through the liver and back to the heart": "",
  "The nerve pathway connecting the enteric nervous system to the liver": "",
  "The enterohepatic circulation is an efficient recycling system in which bile salts secreted into the duodenum are reabsorbed by active transport in the terminal ileum (about 95% efficiency), returned to the liver via the hepatic portal vein, and re-secreted in bile. This cycle occurs 6 to 8 times per day and conserves the body's limited bile salt pool.": "",
  "What is the sphincter of Oddi?": "",
  "A muscular valve at the junction of the esophagus and stomach": "",
  "A valve between the ileum and cecum": "",
  "The external anal sphincter that controls defecation": "",
  "A smooth muscle sphincter surrounding the hepatopancreatic ampulla that controls the release of bile and pancreatic juice into the duodenum": "",
  "The sphincter of Oddi is a smooth muscle valve located at the hepatopancreatic ampulla (ampulla of Vater) where the common bile duct and main pancreatic duct enter the duodenum. It regulates the flow of bile and pancreatic secretions into the intestine and prevents duodenal contents from refluxing into these ducts.": "",
  "A 45-year-old obese woman presents to the emergency department with severe right upper quadrant pain after eating a fatty meal. An ultrasound reveals stones in the gallbladder and a dilated common bile duct. Which condition best explains her presentation?": "",
  "Acute hepatitis A infection": "",
  "Peptic ulcer disease from H. pylori": "",
  "Acute pancreatitis from alcohol use": "",
  "Cholelithiasis with choledocholithiasis (gallstones obstructing the common bile duct)": "",
  "This patient's presentation is classic for symptomatic cholelithiasis: an obese female with postprandial RUQ pain after a fatty meal. The dilated common bile duct indicates a gallstone has migrated into and is obstructing the duct (choledocholithiasis), which can lead to biliary colic, cholangitis, or pancreatitis if untreated.": "",
  "A chronic alcoholic is admitted with severe epigastric pain radiating to his back, nausea, and vomiting. His serum lipase is elevated to 5 times the upper limit of normal. Which organ is inflamed, and what is happening at the cellular level?": "",
  "The pancreas is inflamed; premature activation of pancreatic enzymes is causing autodigestion of pancreatic tissue": "",
  "The gallbladder is inflamed; bile salts are leaking into the blood": "",
  "The liver is inflamed; hepatocytes are releasing lipase into the blood": "",
  "The stomach is inflamed; excessive acid is eroding the mucosal lining": "",
  "Elevated serum lipase is the most sensitive and specific marker for acute pancreatitis. Alcohol metabolites cause premature activation of trypsin within the pancreas, which triggers a cascade activating other zymogens. These active enzymes then digest the pancreatic tissue itself (autodigestion), causing severe inflammation, necrosis, and potentially life-threatening complications.": "",
  "A patient with advanced liver cirrhosis develops esophageal varices and ascites. His laboratory tests show low albumin and prolonged prothrombin time. A medical student asks how liver cirrhosis leads to all of these findings. Which explanation is correct?": "",
  "Cirrhosis only affects bile production, and the other symptoms are caused by a separate kidney disease": "",
  "Scar tissue obstructs hepatic blood flow causing portal hypertension (varices, ascites), while impaired hepatocyte function reduces albumin and clotting factor synthesis": "",
  "Cirrhosis causes the liver to overproduce bile, which damages blood vessels and leaks into the abdomen": "",
  "The fibrotic liver compresses the aorta, reducing blood flow to all abdominal organs": "",
  "Cirrhosis causes two major problems: (1) architectural distortion of the liver creates resistance to blood flow through the portal system, leading to portal hypertension, which causes esophageal varices and contributes to ascites; (2) the loss of functional hepatocytes impairs synthesis of albumin (causing low oncotic pressure and worsening ascites) and clotting factors (causing prolonged PT and bleeding risk).": "",
  "A patient has her gallbladder surgically removed (cholecystectomy) due to recurrent gallstone attacks. She asks her surgeon whether she will still be able to digest fats. What is the most accurate response?": "",
  "She will never be able to digest fats again and must avoid all dietary fat permanently": "",
  "The liver will continue to produce bile that drains directly into the duodenum, but she may have difficulty with large, fatty meals since bile can no longer be stored and concentrated": "",
  "The pancreas will take over bile production within a few weeks": "",
  "The stomach will compensate by increasing acid production to dissolve fats": "",
  "After cholecystectomy, the liver continues to produce bile, which flows continuously through the common bile duct into the duodenum. However, without the gallbladder to store and concentrate bile, there is no reservoir to release a large bolus of concentrated bile in response to a fatty meal, so patients may experience bloating, diarrhea, or discomfort with large amounts of fat.": "",
  "A newborn develops jaundice on day two of life. The pediatrician explains that this is physiological jaundice due to the newborn's immature liver. What is happening at the metabolic level?": "",
  "The newborn's liver is producing too much bile, overwhelming the intestines": "",
  "The immature liver cannot conjugate bilirubin efficiently, causing unconjugated bilirubin to accumulate in the blood and deposit in the skin": "",
  "The newborn has a gallstone blocking the bile duct": "",
  "The newborn's red blood cells are normal, but the kidneys cannot excrete bilirubin": "",
  "Neonatal physiological jaundice occurs because the newborn's liver has immature UDP-glucuronyl transferase enzyme activity, which is needed to conjugate (water-solubilize) bilirubin for excretion in bile. Combined with a higher rate of red blood cell turnover (breaking down fetal hemoglobin), this leads to transient unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia that typically resolves within 1-2 weeks.": "",
  "A patient with chronic hepatitis C is found to have prolonged bleeding after a dental procedure. Blood tests show a prolonged prothrombin time (PT). The dentist consults a physician, who explains that the bleeding is related to liver dysfunction. What is the connection?": "",
  "Hepatitis C causes the kidneys to excrete clotting factors in the urine": "",
  "The liver overproduces anticoagulant proteins that prevent blood from clotting": "",
  "Hepatitis C virus directly destroys platelets in the bloodstream": "",
  "The damaged liver cannot adequately synthesize clotting factors (including factors II, VII, IX, X, and fibrinogen), leading to impaired coagulation": "",
  "The liver synthesizes nearly all coagulation factors, including the vitamin K-dependent factors (II, VII, IX, X) and fibrinogen. When hepatocytes are damaged by chronic hepatitis, their synthetic capacity declines, leading to decreased clotting factor production and a prolonged prothrombin time, which manifests as increased bleeding tendency.": "",
  "A patient presents with clay-colored (pale) stools, dark urine, and jaundice. A CT scan reveals a mass at the head of the pancreas compressing the common bile duct. How do these findings explain the symptoms?": "",
  "Compression of the common bile duct prevents bile from reaching the intestine, so bilirubin backs up into the blood (jaundice, dark urine) and stool lacks the bile pigments that give it color (pale stools)": "",
  "The tumor is directly invading the liver and destroying all hepatocytes": "",
  "The pancreatic mass is blocking the portal vein, preventing all blood flow to the liver": "",
  "The pancreatic tumor is producing excess bilirubin that overflows into urine and stool": "",
  "Obstruction of the common bile duct (obstructive/post-hepatic jaundice) prevents conjugated bilirubin from reaching the intestine. Without bilirubin being converted to stercobilin by gut bacteria, stools become pale (acholic). The conjugated bilirubin backs up into the blood, causing jaundice, and is filtered by the kidneys, causing dark (tea-colored) urine.": "",
  "A student in an anatomy lab is dissecting the hepatic region and identifies a small structure attached to the inferior surface of the liver, connected to the common hepatic duct via the cystic duct. The professor asks what role CCK plays in the function of this structure. What is the correct answer?": "",
  "CCK inhibits the gallbladder from releasing bile until digestion is complete": "",
  "CCK causes the structure to produce more bile": "",
  "CCK causes the gallbladder to contract and release stored, concentrated bile into the cystic duct and then the common bile duct for delivery to the duodenum": "",
  "CCK causes the gallbladder to absorb bile salts from the bloodstream": "",
  "When fat and protein enter the duodenum, I-cells release CCK into the bloodstream. CCK stimulates smooth muscle contraction of the gallbladder wall, forcing stored concentrated bile through the cystic duct into the common bile duct and out through the sphincter of Oddi into the duodenum, where bile salts emulsify dietary fats.": "",
  "A 55-year-old man with a history of heavy alcohol use is diagnosed with chronic pancreatitis. He reports oily, foul-smelling stools and has lost significant weight. His doctor prescribes pancreatic enzyme replacement therapy. Why does chronic pancreatitis cause these symptoms?": "",
  "Chronic pancreatitis causes the gallbladder to stop releasing bile, preventing fat absorption": "",
  "Progressive destruction of pancreatic acinar cells reduces secretion of lipase, proteases, and amylase, leading to maldigestion of fats (steatorrhea), proteins, and carbohydrates": "",
  "Chronic pancreatitis blocks the hepatic portal vein, preventing nutrient delivery to the liver": "",
  "The damaged pancreas releases toxins that destroy the intestinal villi": "",
  "Chronic pancreatitis leads to progressive fibrosis and destruction of the exocrine pancreatic tissue (acinar cells). When more than 90% of exocrine function is lost, the pancreas cannot produce sufficient lipase, proteases, and amylase, resulting in maldigestion. Fat maldigestion is most clinically apparent, manifesting as steatorrhea (oily, foul-smelling stools) and weight loss due to caloric wasting.": "",
  "A patient undergoing chemotherapy develops severe mucositis (inflammation of the oral mucosa) and xerostomia (dry mouth). The oncology nurse explains that the loss of saliva affects more than just comfort. What important digestive and protective functions of saliva are being compromised?": "",
  "Only the ability to taste food is affected": "",
  "Loss of salivary amylase (starch digestion), lysozyme (antibacterial defense), bicarbonate (pH buffering), and mucus (lubrication for swallowing) compromises both digestion and oral health": "",
  "Only mechanical digestion in the mouth is affected because saliva has no chemical functions": "",
  "The only consequence is difficulty swallowing pills, with no other functional impact": "",
  "Saliva serves multiple critical functions: salivary amylase initiates starch digestion, lysozyme and IgA provide antimicrobial defense, bicarbonate buffers acids to protect tooth enamel, mucus lubricates food for swallowing, and water dissolves molecules for taste perception. Chemotherapy-induced xerostomia increases the risk of dental caries, oral infections, difficulty swallowing, and impaired initial digestion.": ""
}